<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="1767" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1767">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 419.11D29/90.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to Minister <persName type="to">Price</persName>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-14">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 14, 1915</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your April 26, and despatch 484. In Department’s opinion next to last
                                paragraph Foreign Office note April 24 indicates Panama will expect
                                arbitrator to entertain evidence and pass upon questions thus raised
                                in considering indemnities to be paid by Panama. The question to be
                                submitted to arbitrator if appointed should merely be amount of
                                damages sustained by injured parties and it should clearly appear in
                                agreement that Panama undertakes to pay indemnities without regard
                                to circumstances affecting riot. If Panama now ready to pay
                                indemnities, however, it appears appropriate to Department that the
                                two Governments should first discuss amount of award, having in view
                                an agreement, before the necessity of appointing arbitrator is
                                considered. Report earliest possible moment.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan.</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>